Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 2cm chunks. Halve and peel the @red onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Trim the @courgette{1} then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @flaked almonds{15%g} and dry-fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> Watch the almonds like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Transfer the almonds to a #board{} once toasted and roughly chop. Set aside.

Pop the diced sweet potato onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{20-22%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(stems and leaves). Pop the parsley and almonds into a #bowl{} with the @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the drizzle. Mix together then set aside.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{750%ml} for the stock into a medium #saucepan{} on high heat. Add the @chicken stock paste{20%g} and stir to combine. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to the lowest setting.

Pop your (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat. Add the @British smoked bacon lardons{90%g}. Stir-fry until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the onion and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook lardons thoroughly.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g} to the pan and reduce the heat to medium. Stir and cook until the edges of the rice are translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add a ladle of your stock. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock. Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time. The cooking time should take ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle. Stir the courgette into the risotto after ~{10%minutes} of cooking time.

Once the rice is cooked, gently stir through the cooked sweet potato. Mix in the @butter{20%g} and @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated). Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if needed.

Spoon the risotto into your #bowls{}. Finish with a spoonful of the parsley and almond drizzle over the top. Enjoy!